    {
        "content": "<p>Don't use tactic mode for anything other than proofs. You will get a lot of weird errors like this.</p>\n<p>(The fundamental reason for this principle is as follows: when reading a tactic mode block, it is difficult to actually tell what term is being expressed. For proofs, this is fine because any two proofs of the same proposition are equal.)</p>",
        "id": 439157880,
        "sender_full_name": "Mitchell Lee",
        "timestamp": 1715926887
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Cool, thanks. I'll keep that in mind.</p>",
        "id": 439158264,
        "sender_full_name": "Vivek Rajesh Joshi",
        "timestamp": 1715927059
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here is a detailed explanation of why this error actually occurs. Imagine that it were possible to use <code>rcases</code> for something other than a proof. Then, you could have something like this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kd\">def</span> <span class=\"n\">f</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">Nat</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span> <span class=\"kd\">by</span>\n  <span class=\"n\">rcases</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Nat.le_or_le</span> <span class=\"n\">x</span> <span class=\"mi\">5</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">x</span> <span class=\"bp\">≤</span> <span class=\"mi\">5</span> <span class=\"bp\">∨</span> <span class=\"mi\">5</span> <span class=\"bp\">≤</span> <span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n  <span class=\"bp\">·</span> <span class=\"n\">exact</span> <span class=\"mi\">0</span>\n  <span class=\"bp\">·</span> <span class=\"n\">exact</span> <span class=\"mi\">1</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>But what would happen if <code>x = 5</code>? Then both conditions <code>x ≤ 5</code> and <code>5 ≤ x</code> would hold, so it's not clear whether <code>f 5</code> should be <code>0</code> or <code>1</code>.</p>\n<p>(Note that there is a definition <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Or.by_cases#doc\">docs#Or.by_cases</a> that you could use to \"Construct a non-Prop by cases on an Or\". But it only works if the left conjunct is decidable.)</p>",
        "id": 439160200,
        "sender_full_name": "Mitchell Lee",
        "timestamp": 1715927976
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Just to be clear -- Mitchell's example can be extended to a example where you prove <code>False</code>, if you allow <code>cases</code> to work when your goal isn't a true/false statement.</p>",
        "id": 439183057,
